        "text": "*[Bug 19091] as.numeric on macOS aarch64 rounds \"0.9999999999999999\" to 1.0 instead of the nearest IEEE 754 double*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19091>\n\nMartin Maechler (<mailto:maechler@stat.math.ethz.ch|maechler@stat.math.ethz.ch>) changed:\n\n           What    |Removed                     |Added\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n             Status|UNCONFIRMED                 |CONFIRMED\n     Ever confirmed|0                           |1\n                 CC|                            |maechler@stat.math.ethz.ch\n\n--- Comment #3 from Martin Maechler (<mailto:maechler@stat.math.ethz.ch|maechler@stat.math.ethz.ch>) ---\nCan you confirm on __all__ platforms that \n```\n&gt; identical(1 - 2^-53, 0.9999999999999999)\n[1] TRUE\n```\nIf yes (which I guess with some confidence),\nthis will make alle the examples\/tests a bit more readable and \"typable\".\nPossibly even more importantly, I think we have on _all_ platforms nowadays\n```\n&gt; stopifnot(identical(2^-53, print(.Machine$double.neg.eps)))\n[1] 1.110223e-16\n&gt; \n```\nand one definition of e_ :=  the Machine's \"neg. epsilon\" is that it is the\nsmallest positive double prec number $\\epsilon$  fulfilling\n$$ 1 - \\epsilon \\neq 1 , $$\nsee\n```\n&gt; e2 &lt;- 2^-(53:54); 1 - e2 &lt; 1\n[1]  TRUE FALSE\n&gt; e2 &lt;- 2^-(52:53); 1 + e2 &gt; 1\n[1]  TRUE FALSE\n```\nNote that the Wikipedia article shows that the definitions are more\nsophisticated, and the above is possible only a \"poor man\"'s version:\n<https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Machine_epsilon>\n\n(In reply to Deepayan Sarkar from comment #2)\n&gt; .............\n&gt; .............\n&gt; (I had initially thought it might have something to do with that\n&gt;  as both macOS and Windows uses clang).\nme, too...\nI think it would even more depend on the C library (libc) implementation\n(and runtime ?).\n\nNote that it *could* be the bug in the respective C library, and python is\nworking around it (and we could too).\nI am marking this `CONFIRMED` now.",
