        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 19091] as.numeric on macOS aarch64 rounds \"0.9999999999999999\" to 1.0 instead of the nearest IEEE 754 double*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19091>\n\n--- Comment #4 from Akitada Kasahara (<mailto:akitadak@econ.osaka-u.ac.jp|akitadak@econ.osaka-u.ac.jp>) ---\nOn my macOS arm64 system, the first identity is not TRUE:\n\n```\nR version 4.6.0 (2026-04-24)\naarch64-apple-darwin23\n\n&gt; identical(1 - 2^-53, 0.9999999999999999)\n[1] FALSE\n```\n\nThe arithmetic expression and the decimal literal give different doubles:\n\n```\n&gt; sprintf(\"%a\", 1 - 2^-53)\n[1] \"0x1.fffffffffffffp-1\"\n&gt; sprintf(\"%a\", 0.9999999999999999)\n[1] \"0x1p+0\"\n```\n\nand the decimal literal is identical to 1:\n\n```\n&gt; identical(0.9999999999999999, 1)\n[1] TRUE\n```\n\nThe `.Machine$double.neg.eps` checks behave as expected:\n\n```\n&gt; identical(2^-53, .Machine$double.neg.eps)\n[1] TRUE\n\n&gt; e2 &lt;- 2^-(53:54); 1 - e2 &lt; 1\n[1]  TRUE FALSE\n\n&gt; e2 &lt;- 2^-(52:53); 1 + e2 &gt; 1\n[1]  TRUE FALSE\n```\n\nSo on this platform, `1 - 2^-53` seems useful as the expected value,\nbut the decimal literal itself still exercises the problematic\nconversion path.\n\nAs an additional check, I also see the expected `TRUE` result on x86_64\nLinux (`rocker\/r-ver:4.4.2` Docker image, R 4.4.2), consistent with\nGabriel Becker's comment #1.",
